			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">--ooc
<br />

<br />
I know that it has been a bit since I have posted about McMad. This story follows this <a href="http://pub149.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisroleplaying.showMessage?topicID=638.topic" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://pub149.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisroleplaying.showMessage?topicID=638.topic</a> post. For those of you that are familar with McMad's wanderings, here is the latest installment. For those of you not familar, I hope you enjoy anyway.
<br />

<br />
--ooc
<br />

<br />

<br />
McMad stops at the entrance to the East Commons and breathes in the cold crisp air. He smiles as he remembers the awe he felt his first time here. The East Commons were once the hub of all merchant activity in Norrath. McMad chuckles as he remembers the sheer terror of entering the marketplace as a young naïve barbarian. All manner of things could be purchased here, from items of the mundane to items of great power and rarity, from clothing to companionship, it could all be found. The big man sighs softly, now the East Commons lie silent as a graveyard, the bustle of the market buried within. McMad sighs again and removes his horned helm to run a four-fingered right hand through his grayed hair. <span style="font-style: italic">Aye, the world has changed. Hardly a place for an old warrior these days</span>, he thinks. 
<br />

<br />
McMad glances back into the Nektulos forest. <span style="font-style: italic">Where will he go now? What will he do? Was it time to hang up his swords?</span> McMad snorts and crams his helm back on his head, “Bah ol’ man, now’s na tha time ta be feelin’ sorry fer yerself.” His hands itch for blood; his arms ache for battle. The brief confrontation with the Neriak guardsmen had done little to calm his nerves. He needs a drink and he knows just the place. There’s one spot in Norrath that will still give McMad the reception he is looking for. Adjusting the white furs that cover his armor, McMad turns east towards the city of Freeport.
<br />

<br />
The hike to Freeport from Neriak is short and McMad reaches the city gates in the late evening hours. The barbarian grins as he pauses just out of sight of the gatekeepers. McMad loosens the straps that secure his various weapons and chuckles. It will be nice to get a drink at Tassel’s, one of his favorite bars in all of Norrath. It’s just getting to North Freeport that’s the problem considering McMad’s been one of the Freeport Militia’s most wanted for some 30 years. The Militia holds the eastern and western gates of Freeport, which makes it impossible to reach the safety of the northern section without passing through the militia’s jurisdiction. Of course, there were other ways into the city. He could sneak in through various secret entrances, but McMad isn’t about to crawl through a sewer. He’ll walk through the gates and kill any man that tries to stop him. Grinning, McMad squares his shoulders and heads towards the city. 
<br />

<br />
“Hold,” the gatesman says, raising his lantern and stepping towards the barbarian, “state your name and business.” 
<br />

<br />
McMad studies the guard as he forms his reply. The gatesman is young, early 20’s McMad would guess, his baby smooth face destroys any hope the guard may have had of being intimidating. “Name’s Battleseeker an’ ah’m jest passin’ through.”
<br />

<br />
The guard stops his advance, “Battleseeker?”
<br />

<br />
McMad keeps his eyes hard but smiles inwardly at the sound of recognition in the guard’s voice, “Aye, tha’s right. McMad Battleseeker.” McMad casually drops his hand to rest on the handle of the axe strapped to his side, ready for the guard to shout for reinforcements. 
<br />

<br />
Suddenly, the guard lowers his voice, “You’re with the Fellowship of Valor then? Come with me, the Captain’s in the back and I’m sure we can get you into the city safely.”
<br />

<br />
McMad stands a moment in stunned silence. This isn’t the reception that he expected. “Whaddya mean?” McMad furrows his eyebrows in confusion.
<br />

<br />
The guard replies, “Everything’s been taken care of. Just follow me and I’ll accompany you to the Northern gates.”
<br />

<br />
The shock sinks in. Someone in the Fellowship has been paying the guards for protection, paying bribes. McMad shakes his head, trying to rid himself of the thoughts. Who? Why? Disappointment and a familiar sadness follows McMad’s feeling of shock. There was a time when simply wearing the torque of the Fellowship of Valor was enough to get a man killed in Militia-controlled Freeport. There was not a Valorite that would be allowed to step foot within Freeport’s walls, now, the torque and the guild name are good for escorted passage. This is too much for the big man. He came here for a reason and, by The Hammers, he would uphold his honor and that of his guild. 
<br />

<br />
McMad resumes walking towards the gate and the guard, “What do yas mean everythin’s been taken care of? Do ya know who ah am?”
<br />

<br />
The guard steps back a bit seeing the strange look in McMad’s eye, “Yes, I’ve heard your name, but there need be no trouble. The Fellowship of Valor has free passage here. It’s been arranged.”
<br />

<br />
The barbarians face reddens with rage, “Arranged? Who arranged it?” McMad is close to shouting now as he increases his pace, bearing down on the guardsman.
<br />

<br />
A look of surprise crosses the guard’s face, “Y..you mean you don’t know?”
<br />

<br />
McMad is shouting now, “Know what? Yas bett..” the barbarian interrupts himself as a posted leaflet catches his eye. Grabbing the back-pedaling guard by the front of his tunic, McMad slams him into the wooden building the flyer is posted on. 
<br />

<br />
Jamming his finger into the parchment under a specific entry, McMad shouts at the trembling guard, “What’s tha say?”
<br />

<br />
“I..it says McMad Battleseeker.” The guard coughs as blood from a broken nose runs into his mouth.
<br />

<br />
”Aye, that it does, an’ what’s it say next ta it? WHAT’S IT SAY?” McMad’s face twists with anger. He can dimly hear the stirrings of other guards in the background as they come to see what the commotion is.
<br />

<br />
Tears begin to well in the young guardsman’s eyes, “Kill on Sight.”
<br />

<br />
McMad roughly throws the guard to the ground, “Yer damn right it does. I spent many a year buildin’ that reputation an’ ah’ll be damned if some kid’s gonna take it away. Why dontcha ask D’Lere if’n I can pass? Ah’m sure he’d love ta hear from me.” McMad glances up to see three more guards running to the aid of the gatekeeper.
<br />

<br />
“Pl..please,” the gatekeeper stutters from his position on the ground, “It doesn’t have to be like this. You don’t have to fight. YOU CAN PASS!”
<br />

<br />
McMad looks down at the form of the sobbing guard as he reaches beneath his furs and pulls a small throwing axe from it’s sheath, “Yas jest don’ get it do yas boy?” McMad draws back his arm and let’s the axe fly at the group of guards, burying it in the shoulder of the leftmost guard. “I came here ta fight.” McMad grins as he unstraps a huge hammer from his belt.
<br />

<br />
The guard’s eyes widen, “Please, please I have a family. Please, I wanted to let you pas…” The guard’s sentence is cut short by the loud cracking sound of McMad’s hammer splitting his skull. 
<br />

<br />
Madness flashes in the barbarian’s good eye as he raises his weapons above his head and shouts, “For Valor!”
<br />

<br />
Bruised, bleeding and broken McMad drags himself into North Freeport, three men lay dead at his feet and four more round the corner just as the Paladins of Marr arrive. The paladins quickly form a guard around the wounded barbarian as the militiamen come to a halt. 
<br />

<br />
“Stand back.” A heavily scarred militiaman growls, “He’s a wanted man.”
<br />

<br />
The mustached Paladin replies, “You know the rules. Any man in North Freeport has safe haven. That is, unless you wish to break the treaty?” The paladin lets an armored hand rest on the hilt of a sword sheathed at this side. 
<br />

<br />
Anger rolls through the group of guardsmen, but the one in the lead replies, “No…no, he has to come outta there soon enough. We can wait Battleseeker.” 
<br />

<br />
McMad begins to chuckle, which soon turns into a fit of bloody coughing, “Could yas wait close ta here? I don’ wanna have tas go huntin’ all over town fer yas when I get done.”
<br />

<br />
The guard snorts and turns to leave, motioning the other guards to follow. As they drift out of earshot, the paladin turns to the barbarian, “They gotcha good this time, didn’t they Mc?”
<br />

<br />
McMad chuckles and leans back against the stone wall, “Aye that they did Arlin, but yas oughta see them. Tha’s one troop that’ll never march in time again.”
<br />

<br />
That paladin laughs and offers a hand to help the barbarian to his feet, “Well get up and let’s get you healed and over to Tassle’s then. I assume that’s why you’re here?”
<br />

<br />
McMad smiles as he takes the offered hand, “Aye, ‘tis”</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
