			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">A cocky smirk splits the barbarian’s face as he steps into the dim interior of Tassle’s bar. This is one of the few places left on Norrath that McMad feels at home in. McMad strides to the bar returning the bartender’s grin with one of his own, claps the nearest man on the back, orders a drink and begins recounting his adventures and listening to the adventures of the familiar faces surrounding him. The bar is crowded and McMad is in his element. The early evening soon turns into early morning and there has been no shortage of ale or exaggerations. McMad is, in fact, in the middle of his own tale of glory when he is interrupted by a familiar voice, “Hello, McMad.”
<br />

<br />
McMad turns and studies the interrupter. He is a tall, young man, with fire-red hair grown long and parting around confident emerald colored eyes. A neatly trimmed goatee frames the man’s mouth. He’s dressed in deep blue-colored neatly pressed robes of a priest, and the symbol on the cover of the worn prayer book in the man’s left hand marks him as a cleric of Mithaniel Marr. Around his neck, the man wears a platinum torque engraved with the symbol of the Fellowship of Valor and, in his right hand, he holds a crushed, blood-covered helm of a Freeport Militaman, which he raises for McMad’s inspection. The man is Seriyn Battleseeker, McMad’s son, and he’s come with a question. Meeting his father’s gaze Seriyn asks, “Why?”
<br />

<br />
The din of the crowded bar quiets noticeably as McMad scratches his thick beard, “Well, because them guards been bleedin’ Freeport and tha Paldin’s o’ Marr fer years now. Yas know that, why ya comin’ here askin’ me ‘bout somethin’ yas already know tha answer too? Ain’ like we havena fought them guards before, ‘sides I’m ‘sposed ta be killed on sight ‘cordin’ ta tha list posted on tha gatehouse.”
<br />

<br />
“Yes, you are on the wanted list of the Freeport Militia, McMad” Seriyn sets the damaged helm on the bar, “but you weren’t attacked, were you? In fact, you were offered an escort to North Freeport, weren’t you?”
<br />

<br />
McMad’s eyes narrow in suspicion, “Wha’s tha got ta do wit’ anythin’?”
<br />

<br />
Seriyn raises an eyebrow, “Well, you did kill or maim a dozen or so men tonight. I suppose I was just trying to understand your reasoning.”
<br />

<br />
“Reasonin’?” McMad chuckles and picks up the helm from the bar top, tossing it to the cleric, “Yas answered yer own question bringin’ that here.”
<br />

<br />
Seriyn catches the helm, “Is that so? Let me tell you a bit about this helmet. It belonged to a young man named Storin Townston. Quite an interesting young man really. Maybe you remember him? Not that I would assume that you remember every life you’ve taken, but Storin might have caught your eye. He was still a boy really, he just passed his 20th year. Good looking kid, had light blonde hair and an innocent face. He’s been pulling gate duty for a couple of months now, so he probably would have been the first guard you ‘spoke’ with tonight. Do you remember him?”
<br />

<br />
McMad shifts on his barstool and leans back against the bar, taking a long draw on the tankard of ale in his hand, “Aye.”
<br />

<br />
Seriyn keeps his look even and waits.
<br />

<br />
McMad’s look turns hard, “I already tol’ ya boy. Any man wearin’ that,” McMad points at the helm Seriyn carries, “deserves what he gets.”
<br />

<br />
“I see,” Seriyn holds the helm up in the torchlight, studying it. “Yes, Storin was a good kid. He’d been with the militia for about a couple of years now. You see McMad, I know a lot about Storin. I’ve been counseling him here at the Temple of Marr for 6 months or so. I know that Storin had a wife and a newborn daughter. I know that he hoped to one day save enough to open an inn on the Eastern side. I know that he did not agree with what the Freeport Militia is doing to the city and he was planning to leave the militia in less than a year. You see, he was close to reaching his goal of having his own inn.” Seriyn turns to face his father, “Would you like to hear more?”
<br />

<br />
McMad takes another drink, “There’s other ways ta make money.”
<br />

<br />
Seriyn meets his father’s gaze, “What would you have had him do? Beg in the street? Prostitute his wife? Or maybe you would have had him risk his life as an adventurer and give his daughter the same quality parenting that you gave me? I am much more practical than that,” Seriyn pauses a moment, “Storin came to the Temple some months ago seeking guidance and forgiveness for the time he was spending as a militiaman, guilt-ridden and bent under the strain of providing for his young wife and daughter. I counseled him to stay with the militia and collect his wages until the day that he could afford to open the inn of his dreams. I assured him that he would be judged by his actions and the faith in his heart, not by the clothes that he wore. After much discussion, he agreed and vowed to live morally within the ranks of the militia. Even promising that members of the Fellowship of Valor that arrived at the gates during his watch would have safe passage to North Freeport. Of course, I did not realize that a man’s character could be changed by something as simple as,“ Seriyn don’s the bloody helm, “this.”
<br />

<br />
McMad slams his ale down on the bar and stands up angrily, “I guess it’s easy fer you ta be righteous, nae? Sittin’ here in yer church prayin’. Do ya know how many o’ my friends I watched lay out there in them streets and die? Do ya? Don’ come in here an’ preach ta me till ya’ve lived it. That boy put on that uniform and that boy knew what that meant. He paid tha price…”
<br />

<br />
“He paid the price?” Seriyn is shouting in anger now, “The price of what? Your ignorance? Your inability to look past the clothes a man wears? I once told someone that the Fellowship of Valor judged a man by his actions. I see now I was wrong, wrong enough that it cost Storin his life.” Seriyn whirls and points an accusing finger at McMad, “You say it is easy for me to act righteous, I say you are the one who is acting. You could have passed into the city without trouble. Storin would have escorted you personally to North Freeport or you could have taken the tunnels. Instead you claim you came here out of some sense of revenge; I say you are a liar. You didn’t come here out of revenge. You came here to kill for the sheer pleasure of the fight.” Only a few feet now separate the shouting cleric and the raging warrior, “You, who calls himself the ‘Sword of Justice’, you’re nothing more than a common murderer. You’re no better than all the men you’ve hunted down over the years. You don’t even deserve to wear this.” Seriyn reaches for the torque of allegiance that every member of the Fellowship of Valor wears.
<br />

<br />
The loud smack of fist hitting flesh seemingly echoes through the now silent bar. It’s followed closely by the thumping sound of Seriyn’s limp body hitting the wooden floor. The patrons of the bar gape momentarily at the twisted face of the barbarian as he looms over the still body of the cleric. The shock passes quickly and a well dressed paladin runs to the fallen cleric. “He’s not breathing,” the paladin states, his stare joining the stares of the rest of the crowd. 
<br />

<br />
McMad’s face turns pale as he glances around the room. The once quiet bar now roars with the sounds of sheathes being emptied. Not even McMad’s reputation would protect him from this, not the death of a priest of Marr, not in North Freeport. “Wait!” the Paladin captain Arlin steps from the crowd, holding his hands in the air, “Wait. You,” Arlin points at the man kneeling over Seriyn’s body, “and you, take Seriyn to the Temple, quickly. The clerics may be able to help him yet.” Arlin looks at the man he once called friend as he addresses the crowd, “Silonest, take McMad wherever he wishes to go.” A robed figure steps from the crowd nodding his acceptance as Arlin continues speaking, “McMad…go with the wizard and….don’t return to North Freeport.”
<br />

<br />
McMad nods softly at the paladin, “Aye, thank yas Arlin.” A look of intense pain and sadness passes the barbarian’s face, “Send me word about the boy?”
<br />

<br />
Arlin sighs heavily and shakes his head, “McMad, if you ever hear from me again it will mean the Cleric is dead. I will not be seeking you to offer condolences.”
<br />

<br />
McMad nods, “Good journeys then.” The big man picks up his pack and then turns to the waiting wizard, “It don’ matter where yas send me.” The wizard nods and speaks briefly in an arcane tongue, making intricate designs in the air with his hands as he does. An instant later, McMad disappears.
<br />

<br />
McMad’s breath catches as the bitter cold of the Great Divide instantly assaults him. Shouldering his pack, McMad disappears into the whirling snow. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
McMad Battleseeker
<br />
Myrmidon of the Fellowship of Valor
<br />
Wolf of the North</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
